DMINE Ag Resilience - Part 1: Demonstration Overview¶

The Climate Impacts Research Consortium (CIRC) data mining stream has developed a set of data mining and machine learning processes, in order to provide a basic example of how we might approach climatic impact prediction over space and time.

Our example is to explore how we might predict economic crop loss over space and time, using data that is extracted from differing sources, transformed, and combined with a response variable that is a approximation of economic crop loss, in dollars.

This notebook provides an overview of our steps for this example, which include:

1. Demo Overview. An overview of the problem.



2. Data Inventory and Harvesting Assessing what datasets are relevant to the problem at hand, then harvesting and assembling that data



3. Data transformation. What steps do we need to take to transform and combine data into a form that is ready to machine learning techniques?



4. Exploratory Data Analysis. After transforming the data, a matrix of all values is generated. From this dataset, what EDA can we perform that will help us to better understand our hypothesis/es?



5. Machine learning model generation, optimization. Which model works best?



6. Model Instantiation. Apply most optimized model to a python API for enabling prediction requests.

1. Demo Overview: Overview of the problem, and summary of datasets¶

Problem question: Can we perform data mining techniques to assemble food resilience data - and construct a machine learning model/models that predicts economic crop loss?¶

Food Resilience NOAA key points (adapted from Third National Climate Assessment - Hatfield, et al, 2014)¶

  1. Climate disruptions to agricultural production have increased over the past 40 years and are projected to increase over the next 25 years. Farmers and ranchers will likely need to increase their rate of innovation and adaptation to keep pace with this projected change.

  2. Crop and livestock production in many agricultural regions will likely decline due to weeds, diseases, insects, and climate-related stresses.

  3. The rising incidence of extreme weather—including heat waves, drought, and very heavy precipitation—will increasingly impact crop and livestock productivity.

  4. Climate-related changes in crop yields and food prices as well as impacts on food processing, storage, and distribution systems can impact food security.

2. Inventory and Harvest Data¶

In this step, we assess what data might be relevant to the issue at hand.

INVENTORY AND HARVEST - Assess problem and assemble universe of data.

Our premise: Insurance claims are filed by farmers nationwide, documenting their monthly losses by commodity (which are summarized and provided to the public at a county level), provides a good estimator of overall food resilience.

Assembled Data:

  • response variable: USDA monthly claims of crop loss, by county, by commodity, for the United States, 1980 to present. this is represented as a set of csv files, one for each year, containing ~ 250,000 records each.
  • feature variables: GRIDMET daily calculated variables, averages monthly across each of county of Washington.

Programming Code:

  1. R is used to extract GRIDMET climate data, and transform data for machine learning analysis.
  2. Python is used to run and implement the machine learning models.

3. Data Transformation¶

In this step, we extract, and format all data - so that it fits into a feature/response matrix. Here, we use R to perform these steps, using the above referenced R programming code (http://github.com/erichseamon/dmine/dmine-gridmet-monthly.R)

4. Exploratory Data Analysis¶

After transforming the data, we performed a fixed amount of EDA, including:

  • linear regression
  • coeeficient calculations
  • anova/manova testing
  • test for collinearity
  • bonferonni outlieer testing

5. Machine learning model generation and optimization¶

In this step, we run our transformed dataset through the following machine learning models. </H4>

  • knn
  • random forest
  • decision tree
  • bagged decision tree
  • bagged random forest

6. Model Instantiation¶

This is a fancy phrase for making the model output dynamically accessible online. Once optimized, we expose the model/models as an application programming interface (API). This has many advantages, a couple being:

  • We can use this approach to enable users to make a request to a model and get a dyanmic response.
  • We can enable other developers, researchers, users, etc - to create their own applications that use our climate prediction API
